3. Production Readiness Review
Issue	Risk	Detail
No parameterized queries	High	sqlsafe.py does identifier quoting, but all filter values are interpolated into SQL strings by builders. One missed edge case = SQL injection. Even with LIKE patterns on user_contains/schema_contains — special characters (%, _) in user input could leak.
session.sql(sql).to_pandas() on every query	Medium	No async execution. No result set streaming for large results. A slow query blocks the Streamlit rerun thread.
No warehouse isolation	Medium	All queries run on whatever warehouse the SiS app owner role uses. A heavy Operations drilldown competes with the Overview first-paint. No multi-cluster or dedicated reader warehouse strategy.
Cache invalidation is global	Medium	bump_refresh_salt() busts ALL cached queries for that user session. A user refreshing Cost data also invalidates Operations cache.
No rate limiting on execute_statement	Medium	Operator actions (settings updates, alert ack) have no throttle. A misclick loop could hammer Snowflake.
Hardcoded company scope	Low	Adding a third company requires a code change and redeploy. Not a config change.
No health check endpoint	Low	No way for external monitoring to verify the app is alive and connected.
RBAC is convenience, not enforcement	Medium	Company scoping is a WHERE clause filter, not a Snowflake row access policy. A user with the app's owner role and SQL access bypasses all scoping. README acknowledges this, but auditors won't accept "it's documented" as mitigation.
Opportunities:

Materialized view on MART_EXEC_BOARD (it's already a scheduled refresh — make it a Dynamic Table)
Pre-aggregate chargeback by department into a daily fact (avoid runtime GROUP BY on ACCOUNT_USAGE)
Move anomaly detection to a scheduled task writing to FACT_ANOMALY_DAILY instead of computing in Python on every page load
