6. "What Am I Missing?"
Multi-account. The entire app assumes one Snowflake account. Enterprise customers have 5-50 accounts. This architecture cannot scale to org-level visibility without a fundamental rewrite.

Data retention policy. Fact tables grow forever. No purge strategy documented. After 12 months of hourly facts, those tables will be large and the app's own storage cost becomes non-trivial.

Concurrent user load. SiS apps share a single session context per app instance. Under 20+ concurrent users, the app will exhibit session state collisions or extreme memory pressure. No load testing mentioned.

Upgrade path. 13 migrations and counting. What happens when V014 needs to ALTER a table that V002 created? No rollback scripts. No blue-green deployment strategy.

Audit trail. Operator actions (settings changes, alert acks) write to Snowflake tables, but there's no immutable audit log. An operator could UPDATE their own audit records.

Time zone handling. All timestamps appear to use server/account time zone. For globally distributed teams, this is a source of confusion. No user-local time zone support.

Data sovereignty. If ALFA operates in regulated industries (insurance — "Trexis" suggests auto insurance), there may be requirements about who can view cost/usage data. The RBAC model is role-based page filtering, not data-level access control.

Disaster recovery. If DBA_MAINT_DB.OVERWATCH is dropped or corrupted, the entire app fails. No documented recovery procedure beyond "re-run migrations."

