What I Genuinely Dislike
The Security page is a fig leaf. Four basic panels pretending to be security monitoring. It would embarrass you in front of a CISO. Either build real security operations (privilege escalation detection, impossible travel, data exfiltration patterns) or remove it entirely and stop claiming the app covers security.

The architecture is allergic to Snowflake-native features. You build a custom alert engine instead of using CREATE ALERT. You build custom scheduling instead of using Dynamic Tables. You build custom forecasting instead of using ML.FORECAST. The justifications in ARCHITECTURE.md read like rationalizing unfamiliarity as intentional minimalism. A "Snowflake Command Center" that avoids Snowflake's own platform capabilities looks like it was built by someone who knows Python better than Snowflake.

40+ sections across 7 pages is a content dump, not a product. There's no user journey. No progressive disclosure. No "here's the one thing you need to know right now." The Control Room tries to be this, but it's still a wall of tables. Great monitoring tools are opinionated — they tell you what matters. This app shows you everything and makes you decide.

The innovation ceiling is low. The app is fundamentally a SQL-query-and-display tool with some Python math on top. There's no ML, no predictive capability, no automation, no workflow. It's a better-organized version of running queries in Snowsight. For 2026, that's not enough to impress anyone who's seen Datadog or Monte Carlo.

The "platform score" is arbitrary. The penalty weights (6 pts per critical alert, 0.5 per GB spill, etc.) are magic numbers with no calibration against actual business impact. Why is one critical alert worth 6 points but 10 GB of spill only worth 2.5? These should be configurable and ideally calibrated against historical incident impact — otherwise it's a vanity metric that executives will learn to ignore.
